JAPANESE ENCEPHALITIS AND OTHER - INDIA (20): (WEST BENGAL)
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 11 Dec 2012
Source: SciDev [edited]
http://www.scidev.net/en/south-asia/news/a-second-japanese-encephalitis-strain-is-circulating-in-india.html


Researchers in West Bengal have reported a 2nd strain of the Japanese encephalitis virus (JEV) circulating in the eastern Indian state.

According to a study published online in Virology Journal last month [15 Nov 2012, see reference, below], the researchers confirmed genotype I (GI) of JEV coexisting with the predominant genotype III (GIII) strain in over 1/4th of 135 patients hospitalised for acute encephalitis syndrome.

The GI strain was 1st detected in India 3 years ago in the Gorakhpur area of the northern state of Uttar Pradesh.

Led by Shyamalendu Chatterjee at the virus unit of the Indian Council of Medical Research (ICMR) in Kolkata, the researchers have now confirmed the GI strain in the samples of blood and fluid from brain and spinal column of patients admitted to government hospitals in 8 West Bengal districts between July-December 2010.

JE, which causes brain fever, is rampant in West Bengal despite an active vaccination programme.

The ICMR scientists, who were joined by Subhra Kanti Mukhopadhyay from the microbiology department of the University of Burdwan, were unable to ascertain how the GI strain, earlier reported circulating in South Korea, Thailand and China, had reached India.

But, the researchers said the possibilities were that the GI strains were brought in by travellers, migratory birds (such as herons), or mosquitoes blown in by cyclonic winds. Domestic pigs are known reservoirs of JEV.

Transmitted to humans by [several species of] _Culex _ mosquitoes, the symptoms of JE include severe rigors, convulsions and high temperature. Patients may go into coma, and the fatality rate is high among child victims.

1st isolated in Japan in 1935, JEV has become a major public health menace with a worldwide case-fatality rate of 30 per cent, and 30-50 per cent of survivors develop permanent brain damage.

The isolation of the GI strain in West Bengal has cast doubts about the efficacy of vaccines currently used against JE derived from the GIII strain. "In future, a JE outbreak is quite likely in the state if this vaccine fails to protect sufficiently against GI of JEV," the researchers noted in their study.

Other experts said there was no cause for panic. "GIII-derived vaccine is used in countries where the GI strain is prevalent and has been found to be effective. I do not think there is any risk," Komal Kushwaha, a physician at the Baba Raghav Das Medical College in Gorakhpur, told SciDev.Net.

Kushwaha suggested carrying out a study by completely immunising one district and keeping another as control over a period of 2 years.

[Byline: Archita Bhatta]

Reference:
Arindam Sarkar, Debjani Taraphdar, Subhra Kanti Mukhopadhyay, Sekhar Chakrabarti and Shyamalendu Chatterjee. Molecular evidence for the occurrence of Japanese encephalitis virus genotype I and III infection associated with acute Encephalitis in Patients of West Bengal, India, 2010. Virology Journal 9:271. 2012.

Abstract (provisional)

Background:
Japanese encephalitis virus (JEV), a mosquito-borne zoonotic pathogen, is the sole etiologic agent of Japanese encephalitis (JE), a neurotropic killer disease which is one of the major causes of viral encephalitis worldwide, with prime public health concern. JE was 1st reported in the state of West Bengal, India in 1973. Since then, it has been reported every year from different districts of the state, although vaccination has already been done, indicating that there might be either partial coverage of the vaccine or the emergence of a mutated/new strain of JEV. To understand JEV genotype distribution, we conducted a molecular epidemiological study on a total of 135 serum/cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) samples referred and/or collected from clinically suspected patients with acute encephalitis syndrome (AES) admitted in different district hospitals of West Bengal, India, 2010.

Findings:
JEV etiology was confirmed in 36/135 (26 per cent) and 13/61 (21 per cent) 2-15 day febrile illness samples from AES cases by analyzing Mac-ELISA followed by RT-PCR tests, respectively. Phylogenetic analysis based on complete envelope gene sequences of 13 isolates showed the emergence of JEV genotype I (GI) co-circulating with genotype III (GIII).

Conclusion:
This study represents the 1st report of JEV GI with GIII co-circulating in West Bengal. The efficacy of the vaccine (derived from the JEV GIII strain SA-14-14-2) to protect against emerging JEV GI needs careful evaluation. In future, a JE outbreak is quite likely in the state if this vaccine fails to protect sufficiently against GI of JEV.

