Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Travelers would not be the source of JEV GI in West Bengal state because viremias in humans are not adequate to infect mosquito vectors that would lead to ongoing virus transmission. It does seem unlikely that the JEV GIII vaccine would fail to protect people from JEV GI infection. Studies using animal models would confirm or discard effective cross-protection. It will be interesting to see which of these genotypes predominates in West Bengal over time and whether individuals who have been vaccinated recently with the GIII vaccine develop clinical disease from JEV infections. If protection is not adequate, the vaccination strategy in eastern India will need to be reevaluated.

Reports of the etiology of acute encephalitis syndrome (AES) in eastern India have been confusing. Some attribute all of the AES cases to JEV infection, others to a small proportion, or to none of them. This report confirms JEV as one of the etiological agents responsible for AES.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of West Bengal state can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/2iyC. - Mod.TY]
